Problem 1

data("brfss_smart2010")
brfss = janitor::clean_names(brfss_smart2010) %>% 
  #Focus on the Overall Health topic
  filter(topic == "Overall Health") %>% 
  #include only responses from Excellent to Poor (i.e. no pre-collapsed categories)
  filter(response == "Excellent" | response == "Very good" | response == "Good" | response == "Fair" | response == "Poor") %>%
  #organize responses as a factor taking levels from Excellent to Poor
  spread(., key = "response", value = "data_value")

In 2002, which states were observed at 7 locations?

brfss2002 = filter(brfss, year == 2002) %>% 
  group_by(locationabbr) %>% 
  summarize(location_num = length(unique(locationdesc))) 
filter(brfss2002, location_num == 7)

Make a spaghetti plot that shows the number of observations in each state from 2002 to 2010.

brfss %>%
  group_by(locationabbr, year) %>%
  summarize(n = sum(sample_size)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = n, color = locationabbr)) + 
    geom_point() + 
    geom_line()

Make a table showing, for the years 2002, 2006, and 2010, the mean and standard deviation of the proportion of Excellent responses across locations in NY State.

brfss_Excellent = filter(brfss, brfss$locationabbr == "NY") %>% 
  filter(., year == 2002 | year == 2006 | year == 2010)

brfss_Excellent %>%
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(mean_proportion = mean(Excellent, na.rm = TRUE), 
       sd_proportion = sd(Excellent, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  knitr::kable(digits = 1)
year mean_proportion sd_proportion
2002 24.0 4.5
2006 22.5 4.0
2010 22.7 3.6

For each year and state, compute the average proportion in each response category (taking the average across locations in a state). Make a five-panel plot that shows, for each response category separately, the distribution of these state-level averages over time.

ggplotExce = brfss %>%
  group_by(year, locationabbr) %>% 
  mutate(mean_proportion = mean(Excellent, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = locationabbr, y = mean_proportion, color = year)) + 
    geom_point() +
    labs(title = "Excellent Proportion")

ggplotVeryg = brfss %>%
  group_by(year, locationabbr) %>% 
  mutate(mean_proportion = mean(`Very good`, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = locationabbr, y = mean_proportion, color = year)) + 
    geom_point() +
      labs(title = "Very good Proportion")

ggplotFair = brfss %>%
  group_by(year, locationabbr) %>% 
  mutate(mean_proportion = mean(Fair, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = locationabbr, y = mean_proportion, color = year)) + 
    geom_point() +
      labs(title = "Fair Proportion")

ggplotGood = brfss %>%
  group_by(year, locationabbr) %>% 
  mutate(mean_proportion = mean(Good, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = locationabbr, y = mean_proportion, color = year)) + 
    geom_point() +
      labs(title = "Good Proportion")

ggplotPoor = brfss %>%
  group_by(year, locationabbr) %>% 
  mutate(mean_proportion = mean(Poor, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = locationabbr, y = mean_proportion, color = year)) + 
    geom_point() +
      labs(title = "Poor Proportion")

(ggplotExce + ggplotVeryg + ggplotGood) / (ggplotPoor + ggplotFair)

Make a table showing the mean hour of the day at which Pink Lady Apples and Coffee Ice Cream are ordered on each day of the week; format this table for human readers (i.e.produce a 2 x 7 table).

instacart_data %>%
  filter(product_name == "Pink Lady Apples" | product_name == "Coffee Ice Cream") %>% 
  group_by(product_name, order_dow) %>%
  summarize(mean_hour = mean(order_hour_of_day)) %>%
